d on male converts’ reclamation of domestic space; and radical rupture from a post-industrial “culture of disposability.” By contrasting the ministries’ logic of addiction with that of biomedicine, Hansen rethinks roads to recovery, discovering unexpected convergences with biomedicine while revealing the allure of street corner ministries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxPentacostal churches. 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxPentecostal churches. 0aMasculinityzPuerto Rico. 0aRecovery movementxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRecovery movementzPuerto Rico. 0aSubstance abusexReligious aspectsxPentacostal churches. 0aSubstance abusexReligious aspectsxPentecostal churches. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aalternative masculinities.  aascetic practice.  ablack neighborhoods.  achristianity.  acultural anthropology.  aculture of disposability.  aethnographic.  aex addicts.  alatino neighborhoods.  amainland.  amale converts.  aministry converts.  amysticism.  aother worldliness.  aovercoming addiction.  apentecostal ministries.  apentecostalism.  apoor minorities.  apsychiatry.  apuerto rico.  areligion.  aself transformation.  aspiritual power.  aspiritual victory.  astreet ministries.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029803340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520970168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520970168/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b20